<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN COMPANIES OFFER FEWER YEAR-END BONUSES THIS YEAR: POLL
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Jan.  13 (CNA) 01/13/07  18:29:43 (By Y.F. Low)
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies in Taiwan are offering bonuses of 2.02-months'
salary on average for their employees this year, down from
3.07-months' salary last year, according to the results of a
survey released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by 1111 Job Bank between Dec. 28 and Jan.
11 among 531 workers serving in foreign companies in Taiwan,
shows that 50.28 percent of the respondents prefer to work for
foreign companies because they offer better benefits.
</P>
<P>
While 40.68 percent of the respondents were attracted by the high
salaries offered by foreign companies, 31.64 percent were
impressed by the international perspective provided by foreign
companies.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey found that only 62.71 percent of the
respondents receive year-end bonuses at the Lunar New Year
holiday.
</P>
<P>
Of the remaining 37.29 percent of respondents who do not get
year-end bonuses, 28.79 percent receive performance-based bonuses
at the end of the year, 24.24 percent get gift vouchers, 22.73
percent receive dividends, 15.15 percent get shares, 12.12
percent get red envelopes containing cash and 9.09 percent get
electrical appliances.
</P>
<P>
Of the respondents who receive year-end bonuses, most get 0.5-1
months' salary, which accounts for 28.83 percent, followed by
1.5-2 months' salary, which accounts for 21.62 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 55 percent of the respondents are positive about their
companies' development in Taiwan in 2007, and 27 percent said
their companies are planning to expand their staff numbers this
year.
</P>
